<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to WHO, frozen shoulder is prevalent among adults between the ages of 40 to 70 years. Studies further conclude that about 3% of the world population will experience "adhesive capsulitis (medical term for frozen shoulder)" at least once in their lifetime.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The risk of developing frozen shoulder is higher in diabetic patients or those who have just recovered from conditions that prevented the movement of the arm, for example, a mastectomy or a stroke.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">For some, the pain may become worse at night or during cold weather, while others may not feel any exceptional pain.</span>

<b>2 Strengthening And Stretching Exercises For A Frozen Shoulder</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Stretching exercises is one of the effective ways to treat frozen shoulder. Make sure your shoulder is warmed up before performing any of the following exercises. You can achieve that by taking a warm 5-10 minutes shower. Remember, only stretch to the level of tension and not pain.</span>

<b>Pendulum stretch</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">First, while standing, rest one hand on a table and freely relax the affected shoulder (the other hand). Swing the affected arm in a circle. Perform up to 10 revolutions in a day.</span>

<b>Towel stretch</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Hold one end of a towel around the waist region of your back, hold the other edge with the other hand. Now, stretch your hands outwards to hold the towel horizontally. Maintain this position for a couple of minutes.</span>

<b>Foods To Avoid During Symptoms Of Frozen Shoulder</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sugar and refined carbs</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Trans fats</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Alcohol</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Glutinous grains such as barley, rye, and wheat.</span>

